# Overload alternatives must be chosen against ALL surrounding
# constraints, not greedily.
#
# `pick`: with a union-typed input, the quote body `(@x toFloat)`
# distributes over the union's members (int -> float, float -> float),
# so the thunk is ( -- float) and both iff branches agree with the
# declared output. (A fully generic `(a -- float)` declaration is
# correctly rejected: the body only works for the numeric
# instantiations, and a generic must hold for every instantiation.)
def pick (int | float -- float)
  x!
  true (@x toFloat) (1.5) iff
end
3 pick str wl

# `(toFloat)` with no pinned input infers as a multi-arm overloaded
# quote: (str -- Maybe[float]) | (int -- float) | (float -- float).
# `map` over [int] must select the int arm — the list operand decides,
# not the first arm that unifies.
[1 2 3] (toFloat) map (str wl) each
